if you're
going to lower tax rates.

17:36.155 --> 17:37.657 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's clearly what we're
working on doing.

17:37.690 --> 17:40.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's what the House blueprint
that we ran
on does do.

17:40.660 --> 17:45.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It does affect both what we call
the individual
side of the tax code and the
business side

17:45.264 --> 17:46.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of the tax code.

17:46.699 --> 17:50.036 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we propose it on a
revenue-neutral basis.

17:50.069 --> 17:53.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we also propose permanent
tax reform.

17:53.339 --> 17:58.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When we did the 2001 and 2003
tax cuts in
the Bush administration, those
were only individual

17:58.811 --> 18:02.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
tax cuts, which you can actually
make those
temporary.

18:02.615 --> 18:04.250 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You can't do that on the
business side of
the code.

18:04.283 --> 18:06.018 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It actually doesn't work.

18:06.052 --> 18:08.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It produces a lot of uncertainty
for businesses.

18:08.421 --> 18:12.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't completely redesign
the budget tax
system for nine-and-a-half
years, and then

18:12.792 --> 18:15.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
flip it back in 10 years.

18:15.328 --> 18:16.395 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't work like that.

18:16.429 --> 18:17.763 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it has to be permanent.

18:17.797 --> 18:23.102 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, we do envision
revenue-neutral tax reform
that is permanent.

18:23.135 --> 18:27.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
With good comprehensive
across-the-board tax
reform, we really believe we can
get the kind

18:27.573 --> 18:31.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of economic growth we need which
will solve
so many problems we have in this
country.

18:31.277 --> 18:37.316 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And fundamental tax reform is
critical, because
now we have the worst tax code
in the industrialized

18:37.350 --> 18:38.317 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
world, bar none.

18:38.351 --> 18:40.186 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, no domestic
spending cuts?

18:40.219 --> 18:43.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I ask because a Republican study
group last
year was talking about $7.5
