38:21.900 --> 38:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so have the other tumors."

38:23.201 --> 38:24.502 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

38:24.536 --> 38:25.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAIN ALGAZI, Skin Cancer
Specialist: My name
is Alain Algazi.

38:25.203 --> 38:26.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm an oncologist.

38:26.437 --> 38:29.674 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I specialize in head, neck
cancer, and melanoma.

38:29.707 --> 38:33.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I work at the University of
California, San
Francisco.

38:33.711 --> 38:36.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Melinda presented with squamous
cell cancer
in a lymph node.

38:36.514 --> 38:42.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was metastatic, but she was
diagnosed at
a time when we had access to
several new drugs.

38:42.253 --> 38:45.390 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those drugs turn the immune
cells back
on that are in the tumor, and
allow them to

38:45.423 --> 38:47.625 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fight more effectively against
the cancer.

38:47.659 --> 38:51.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, basically, they're taking
your native
immune response and enhancing
it.

38:51.663 --> 38:54.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we caused the tumors to
regress and go
away.

38:54.966 --> 39:00.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MELINDA WELSH: I think it
actually took a
day or two to fully sink in that
my calendar

39:01.005 --> 39:02.974 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
had expanded.

39:03.007 --> 39:10.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
