here.

41:36.728 --> 41:38.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want to live fully in the
present.

41:38.730 --> 41:44.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, just a little
bit of future
is awfully wonderful mixed in
with that.

41:44.168 --> 41:45.436 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

41:45.470 --> 41:47.071 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ALAIN ALGAZI: People come to me,
and they
have low expectations.

41:47.105 --> 41:48.940 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
People think, I'm going to die.

41:48.973 --> 41:51.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And my thought is, it doesn't
have to be that
way.

41:51.409 --> 41:56.514 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have now ways of keeping
people well, not
just for a few months, but for
potentially

41:56.547 --> 41:57.515 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
years.

41:57.548 --> 41:59.384 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So this is a time of hope.

41:59.417 --> 42:03.254 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MELINDA WELSH: "I am still
coming to terms
as best I can with my own
unequivocal transience.

42:03.287 --> 42:06.958 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But, no, I'm not dead yet.

42:06.991 --> 42:11.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When people are surprised to see
me, I tell
them I'm among the early
fortunate.

42:11.963 --> 42:16.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Facing death on a close horizon
has heightened
my awareness that our time on
Earth is finite.

42:16.734 --> 42:24.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But quite unexpectedly, it has
also made me
a living, breathing
advertisement for humanity's

42:24.575 --> 42:25.843 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
hopeful new edge on cancer."

42:25.877 --> 42:29.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That was
Melinda Welsh with
her story.

42:29.113 --> 42:33.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's get a broader look at what
these treatments
may offer and their limits.

42:33.651 --> 42:36.020 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jeffrey Bluestone is a leading
researcher
in this field.

42:36.053 --> 42:40.191 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is the president and CEO of
the Parker
Institute for Cancer
Immunotherapy.

42:40.224 --> 42:45.329 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He's also a professor of
metabolism and endocrinology
at the University of California,
San Francisco,

42:45.363 --> 42:47.064 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
School of Medicine.

42:47.098 --> 42:51.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Matt Richtel is a science
writer who has
covered this extensively for The
New York

42:51.202 --> 42:53.104 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Times.

42:53.137 --> 42:55.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mr. Bluestone, I want to start
with you before
all of our viewers start to call
their oncologists

42:55.706 --> 42:57.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
if they're facing this.

42:57.608 --> 43:02.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is still not quite at the
phase where
we're seeing it effective in,
say, lung cancer,

43:02.313 --> 43:06.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and prostate cancer, and breast
cancer and
the major cancers that so many
people face.

43:06.451 --> 43:08.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BLUESTONE, CEO, Parker
Institute for
Cancer Immunotherapy: Well,
actually, we have

43:08.486 --> 43:11.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
made a tremendous amount of
progress, for
instance, in lung cancer.

43:11.756 --> 43:17.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These so-called immune drugs,
these checkpoint
inhibiters, are now treating a
lot of non-small

43:17.728 --> 43:24.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
cell lung cancers with great
success, in 30
to 40 to 50 percent response
rate, so very

43:24.302 --> 43:27.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
high, as in melanoma, as in some
head and
neck cancer.

43:27.305 --> 43:31.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yes, there are a lot of cancers
we still have
a long ways to go, but in some
of the cancers

43:31.375 --> 43:33.578 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you mentioned, we have actually
made tremendous
progress.

43:33.611 --> 43:35.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: That's great
to hear.

43:35.279 --> 43:37.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Matt Richtel, you have covered
this.

43:37.248 --> 43:41.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have chronicled people who
have fought
through their cancers, had this
sort of immunotherapy

43:41.652 --> 43:43.588 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
work, and also some who haven't.

43:43.621 --> 43:45.756 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What are some of the
shortcomings or limitations?

43:45.790 --> 43:47.525 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MATT RICHTEL, The New York
Times: Yes.

43:47.558 --> 43:52.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
First of all, that was a
marvelous piece that
captured just how remarkable
this science

43:52.430 --> 43:55.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is on the very edge of life and
death.

43:55.833 --> 43:57.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you have asked a great
question.

43:57.702 --> 44:04.442 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the answer is the very thing
that makes
this therapy so potentially
powerful or powerful

44:04.475 --> 44:07.111 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
also causes some challenges.

44:07.144 --> 44:08.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that is this.

44:08.946 --> 44:14.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you soup up or unleash the
immune system,
you have an opportunity to have
it attack

44:14.051 --> 44:16.554 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
healthy organs, healthy cells.

44:16.587 --> 44:22.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so sometimes you see very
challenging
stories where a cancer -- a
tumor will disappear,

44:23.027 --> 44:26.197 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but the person will become sick
with the equivalent
of an autoimmune disorder.

44:26.230 --> 44:31.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, we have with Dr.
Bluestone just
an amazing authority to probably
elaborate

44:31.869 --> 44:32.837 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
on that.

44:32.870 --> 44:34.739 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Mr. Bluestone,
go ahead.

44:34.772 --> 44:35.907 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BLUESTONE: Yes.

44:35.940 --> 44:38.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think that what Matt said
is absolutely
true.

44:38.809 --> 44:41.579 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The immune system is an
incredibly powerful
force.

44:41.612 --> 44:45.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's designed to recognize
everything that
is foreign.

44:45.283 --> 44:49.453 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in the process of doing
that, and when
you unleash it the way these new
drugs do,

44:49.487 --> 44:55.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you can often, not that often,
rare compared
to the response rate get these
autoimmune

44:55.626 --> 44:57.395 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
diseases.

44:57.428 --> 45:00.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At UCSF, we have had several
cases in the
last couple years of patients
who developed

45:00.998 --> 45:06.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
type 1 diabetes, an autoimmune
disease that
causes the destruction of your
insulin-producing

45:06.671 --> 45:08.506 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
cells.

45:08.539 --> 45:12.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And trying to understand how to
control these
side effects is one of the key
areas for the

45:12.176 --> 45:15.246 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Parker Institute, at UCSF as
well.

45:15.279 --> 45:21.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the goal here is to have
this unleashing
of the immune system, which is
key to eliminating

45:21.485 --> 45:27.758 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the cancer, while moderating
this unwanted
attack on your own tissues.

45:27.792 --> 45:31.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Matt Richtel,
with all of
the different scientists that
you have spoken

45:31.262 --> 45:35.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to, where are we in this arc?

45:35.266 --> 45:38.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of the people who have been
profiled
in your story say this is almost
like where

45:38.169 --> 45:40.972 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NASA engineers were in the '60s.

45:41.005 --> 45:42.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATT RICHTEL: Yes.

45:42.573 --> 45:46.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I love that comparison, and I
have heard various
ones along the same lines.

45:46.811 --> 45:50.414 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I can't tell you how wide the
breadth of potential
is.

45:50.448 --> 45:56.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's somewhere on the continuum
from, you
know, marvel of science to
change the world.

45:56.354 --> 45:59.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's what I mean, and then I
will answer
your question directly.

45:59.657 --> 46:05.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Absolutely, we are seeing at
least a marvel
of science, in that people who
were not previously

46:05.262 --> 46:08.199 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
savable from cancer are being
saved.

46:08.232 --> 46:10.134 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That alone is marvelous.

46:10.167 --> 46:14.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the change-the-world end of
the continuum,
we're certainly not there yet,
but the potential

46:14.872 --> 46:19.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exists to attack one of the
biggest killers
in the world.

46:19.944 --> 46:25.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have done away with a lot of
the low-hanging
fruit of what kills us through
things like

46:25.282 --> 46:27.051 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
antibiotics.

46:27.084 --> 46:32.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So now cancer, which many people
never survived
to even get, is the second
leading killer

46:32.089 --> 46:33.624 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in this country.

46:33.658 --> 46:36.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It could change the world if
this hangs on.

46:36.627 --> 46:39.263 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Why are we just still at the
beginnings of
that?

46:39.296 --> 46:43.968 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because, as Jeff -- as Dr.
Bluestone underscored
and as lots of scientists have
told me at

46:44.001 --> 46:51.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this point, we can't yet tell if
more people
will either suffer side effects
or relapse

46:51.842 --> 46:55.079 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ultimately than we know of now.

46:55.112 --> 46:59.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's so early on that we
just can't answer
that question and we probably
won't be able

46:59.650 --> 47:01.786 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to for a decade or so.

47:01.819 --> 47:05.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Jeffrey
Bluestone, is that
about the right timeline?

47:05.956 --> 47:10.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are still those hurdles,
as we heard
in the piece, that the drugs are
still expensive,

47:10.227 --> 47:12.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that there are still lots of
nonresponsive
patients.

47:12.730 --> 47:16.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, as you mentioned, how
do you calibrate
the immune system per patient,
so that it

47:16.701 --> 47:20.004 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
doesn't kind of go overboard and
attack what
we need to survive?

47:20.037 --> 47:26.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BLUESTONE: Yes, we're
certainly at
absolutely the change inflection
point.

47:26.177 --> 47:29.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The world has changed for cancer
therapy with
immunotherapy.

47:29.647 --> 47:34.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's hard to even explain how
different this
approach is.

47:34.852 --> 47:40.624 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead of using poisons to kill
cancer or
to wipe out the cancer cell,
we're actually

47:40.658 --> 47:42.993 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
using our own body to do this.

47:43.027 --> 47:47.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, in this kind of
transformational science,
there's a lot to learn.

47:47.264 --> 47:49.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to learn, what are the
fundamental
rules?

47:49.867 --> 47:55.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we have to learn how to
moderate the drugs
in a way that maximize the
efficacy and minimize

47:55.940 --> 47:57.708 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the toxicity.

47:57.742 --> 48:03.114 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I cannot imagine that, over
the next 10
years, we don't start see a
dramatic change

48:03.147 --> 48:06.584 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the long-term survival of
many of the patients
with many of the cancers.

48:06.617 --> 48:08.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have already seen it in
melanoma.

48:08.886 --> 48:13.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have gone from 5 percent
five-year survival
to 40 percent five-year
survival.

48:13.090 --> 48:14.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have seen it in certain lung
cancers.

48:14.725 --> 48:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, yes, we're right at the
beginning.

48:16.994 --> 48:21.065 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But we're already seeing a
dramatic change
in a lot of these patients.

48:21.098 --> 48:25.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I believe this new science
-- and it truly
is -- bringing together the
science of the

48:25.703 --> 48:30.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
immune system and immunology
with the science
of cancer in ways that we could
never have

48:30.708 --> 48:32.977 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
believed we would be at, at this
point.

48:33.010 --> 48:34.545 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, sure, I'm optimistic.

48:34.578 --> 48:36.313 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I'm excited.

48:36.347 --> 48:40.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm -- every day I go to work, I
just can't
believe we're in this world we
live in now.

48:40.684 --> 48:42.086 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

48:42.119 --> 48:44.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATT RICHTEL: Could I just
underscore something
Dr. Bluestone said?

48:44.455 --> 48:46.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You mentioned I have chronicled
patients.

48:46.123 --> 48:49.727 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of them was a good high
school friend
named Jason Greenstein.

48:49.760 --> 48:54.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when Dr. Bluestone says
treatments have
changed, let me just tell you a
quick anecdote

48:54.532 --> 48:56.901 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that underscores how much.

48:56.934 --> 49:01.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over several years, this friend
of mine, Jason,
went through the traditional
chemotherapy.

49:01.172 --> 49:07.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it ate him alive, just as
chemotherapy
can do, because you're giving
someone toxins.

49:07.912 --> 49:14.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Over the course of literally
weeks when he
took an immunotherapy drug, you
could watch

49:14.185 --> 49:21.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what was like a pumpkin-sized
tumor in his
back disappear by the day in
picture after

49:21.225 --> 49:22.193 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
picture.

49:22.226 --> 49:24.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so that's the kind of
quantum leap.

49:24.128 --> 49:27.298 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, ultimately, he -- my friend
succumbed.

49:27.331 --> 49:31.135 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But that's the kind of quantum
change that
Dr. Bluestone is describing.

49:31.168 --> 49:34.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Matt Richtel
of The New York Times, Jeffrey
Bluestone of

49:34.305 --> 49:36.941 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
UCSF and the Parker Institute,
thanks so much.

49:36.974 --> 49:40.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MATT RICHTEL: Thank you.

49:40.678 --> 49:47.451 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BLUESTONE: Thank you.

49:47.484 --> 49:53.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUDIE CORNISH: Now to our
"NewsHour" Shares,
something that caught our eye
that might be

49:53.891 --> 49:55.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of interest to you, too.

49:55.793 --> 50:00.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more than 60 years, British
researchers
have monitored changes in the
world's atmosphere

50:00.130 --> 50:02.199 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
from a remote lab in Antarctica.

50:02.233 --> 50:06.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, for the first time ever,
this facility
will close, at least
temporarily, to protect

50:06.403 --> 50:08.105 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the safety of its residents.

50:08.138 --> 50:10.307 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The "NewsHour"'s Julia Griffin
explains.

50:10.341 --> 50:17.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIA GRIFFIN: At the bottom of
our planet,
on top of more than 400 feet of
ice, sits

50:17.515 --> 50:20.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a state-of-the-art research
station called
Halley VI.

50:20.718 --> 50:23.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID VAUGHAN, Director of
Science, British
Antarctic Survey: It's an
extraordinary place

50:23.420 --> 50:29.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be, sitting in this, what
feels like a
large ship on the ice, looking
out across

50:29.460 --> 50:32.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the vast expanse of essentially
nothingness.

50:32.429 --> 50:37.801 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIA GRIFFIN: David Vaughan is
director of
science for British Antarctic
Survey, which

50:37.835 --> 50:39.336 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
runs Halley VI.

50:39.370 --> 50:43.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID VAUGHAN: The science that
we do at Halley
isn't just about exploring.

50:43.474 --> 50:51.148 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's actually making
measurements that really
inform how we interact with our
planet, about

50:51.181 --> 50:57.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the risk of severe space weather
storms that
might knock out our satellite
GPS systems.

50:57.054 --> 51:03.294 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's about looking at the
emissions of carbon
dioxide and methane at the last
place on Earth

51:03.327 --> 51:05.095 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that is seeing those emissions.

51:05.129 --> 51:10.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIA GRIFFIN: To do that,
Halley VI is a
feat of engineering in one of
the most extreme

51:10.501 --> 51:12.303 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
environments.

51:12.336 --> 51:19.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Its eight interlocking pods
shield up to 70
researchers and support staff
from freezing.

51:19.743 --> 51:25.549 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special hydraulic legs lift the
pods as snow
accumulates, and when the time
comes, the

51:25.582 --> 51:28.218 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pods can be towed on their
ski-like feet.

51:28.252 --> 51:31.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID VAUGHAN: The ice shelf
itself moves.

51:31.221 --> 51:36.593 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if we're going to maintain
the same geographical
position, we have to be able to
move across

51:36.627 --> 51:37.761 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
the ice.

51:37.795 --> 51:40.297 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JULIA GRIFFIN: Another reason
they might want
to move?

51:40.331 --> 51:44.468 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Should that ice shelf threaten
to become an
iceberg.

51:44.501 --> 51:50.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This summer -- yes, it's summer
in the Southern
Hemisphere -- Halley VI was
already being

51:50.207 --> 51:58.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
towed 15 miles inland to avoid
this decades-old
